      <div class="article-body">
        <p>My journey began in the vibrant pulse of Tunisia, where I was raised amidst the evolving landscape of the capital. In 1978, as the world's eyes were fixed on the World Cup, my family relocated to M&eacute;grine, a southern suburb that would become the backdrop of my early social education. In M&eacute;grine, life centered around the local coffee house&mdash;a quintessential sociological microcosm. At &ldquo;Uncle Mohamed's,&rdquo; the air was thick with tobacco smoke and the clatter of dominoes; it was a sanctuary where the employed, the academic, and the jobless sat as equals. While elders engaged in heated political discourse, I found myself drawn to the quiet intensity of the chess tables. My father had taught me the fundamental moves during the long, expectant afternoons of Ramadan, but our matches ended the day I finally overcame him, and he gracefully retired from our private board.</p>
        <p>The true test of my resolve, however, occurred at the hands of &ldquo;Uncle Arbi,&rdquo; a man of aristocratic bearing whose presence in the coffee house commanded silent respect. When I boldly asked to play him, he dismantled my game five times in a row, his victories punctuated by the stifled giggles of his peers. I left that day feeling the sting of public ridicule, shamed by his dismissal: &ldquo;Come back in six months, young man.&rdquo; It was my father who recognized my despair and bridged the gap between my humiliation and my potential. Through his connection to Slim Bouaziz&mdash;the only Tunisian International Master at the time, famed for drawing against the legendary Korchnoi&mdash;I was granted an audience at the Tunisian Chess Federation. Gifted with a vinyl board and a library of theory, I spent the following year immersed in the mechanics of openings and the logic of endgames. When I finally returned to the coffee house, the &ldquo;systems&rdquo; I had studied allowed me to dismantle the very circle that had once laughed at my efforts.</p>
        <p>Chess, for me, has always been personal. When I immigrated to the United States in the spring of 1991, I stopped playing almost entirely. Just like that, the board folded shut. I moved to Chicago, then to Illinois State University, where I earned my degree in Sociology. Chess wasn&rsquo;t part of the plan anymore.</p>
        <p>That changed in 2007, when I moved to New York City to pursue a Master&rsquo;s in International Affairs at The New School. I was living in Stuyvesant Town, and one afternoon I wandered into the inner park and saw the stone chess tables. Something pulled me back. Just like that, the board opened again.</p>
        <p>The park had its own hierarchy. Regulars claimed certain tables. You had to earn your place. But for someone who had arrived in a new city with no friends, no family, and no community, the tables offered something that nothing else in New York had: a place to sit across from another person and belong, even briefly. Chess became my only way to break through the loneliness of being a stranger in a city that doesn&rsquo;t wait for you to catch up.</p>
        <p>It was at one of those tables that I met William Lombardy&mdash;Bill, as everyone called him. He was already a legend: the youngest player to win the World Junior Championship with a perfect score, Bobby Fischer&rsquo;s second during the 1972 World Championship in Reykjav&iacute;k. But in the park, he was just Bill&mdash;a heavyset man in a worn jacket who played fast, talked freely, and didn&rsquo;t care if you knew his rÃÂ©sumÃÂ©.</p>
        <p>Over coffee at a nearby diner, Bill told me stories about Bobby Fischer that I had never heard&mdash;stories about a boy who was already showing signs of the isolation that would later consume him, and about a chess world that looked the other way because the boy could play. Those conversations planted the seed for everything I would later write about chess and the mind.</p>
        <p>Across all these places and people, the chessboard has remained the one constant&mdash;a portable republic with its own laws, immune to borders, language, or circumstance. From my father&rsquo;s Ramadan lessons to Uncle Arbi&rsquo;s coffee-house gauntlet, from the stone tables of Stuyvesant Town to late-night conversations with Bill Lombardy, the board has been more than a game. It has been a way to enter rooms I had no right to enter, to break through isolation, and to find, in the company of strangers, a conversation and connection that transcends borders and circumstance.</p>
